arrative of agent work from `entire dispatch --since 30d`, (3) hot files and recurring topics from clustering `entire search` hits and recent commits, (4) key contributors from `git shortlog` cross-referenced with checkpoint authors.\n- Activate on natural phrases like \"give me a repo overview\", \"onboard me\", \"what is this repo about\", \"where do I start\".\n- Support a **single guided flow**: produce a structured report first, then offer drill-downs (specific checkpoint, file area, contributor) the user can pick. No separate \"one-shot vs interactive\" mode toggle — the report is the one-shot, the drill-downs are the interactive part.\n- Default to a 30-day dispatch window and a max of 50 `entire search` hits to bound runtime; allow the user to widen explicitly.\n- Use `entire explain --short --no-pager` during the primary flow to collect recent local checkpoint IDs and timestamps for optional drill-down suggestions; treat it as branch-local anchor inventory, not the authoritative repo-wide narrative source.\n- Match the existing skills' robustness floor: handle missing `entire` CLI, unauthenticated state, and empty checkpoint history with clear, header-suppressed messages.\n\n## Non-Goals\n\n- Discovering `entire` commands dynamically. The skill uses the three canonical commands plus standard `git` commands and nothing else.\n- Producing a persistent artifact such as a generated `ONBOARDING.md` (the user can ask the agent to save the output separately if they want).\n- Fully offline operation. The skill requires `entire` for the narrative; if `entire` is unavailable it tells the user and stops, matching the pattern in `skills/explain/SKILL.md`.\n- Shipping outside this repo (e.g., to `~/.claude/skills/` or a separate plugin). It will be picked up by the same install paths as the other skills via the existing `skills` package.\n- A second-tier \"deep tour\" that reads many checkpoint transcripts in full. Drill-down expansion is one checkpoint at a time, on user request.\n\n## Proposal\n\n### Skill identity\n\n- **Skill name:** `project-overview`\n- **File:** `skills/project-overview/SKILL.md` (single file, no helpers — matches `skills/search/`, `skills/explain/`, `skills/what-happened/`, `skills/session-handoff/`)\n- **Frontmatter description:** \"Use when a developer is new to a repo or returning after time away and wants an overview: architecture, recent agent activity, hot files, and key contributors. Triggers on phrases like 'give me a repo overview', 'onboard me', 'where do I start in this repo'.\"\n- **Response header (first response only):** `Entire Project Overview:` — same convention as other skills in this repo. Suppress on early-exit / error responses.\n\n### Command flow\n\nSteps 1–3 are independent and run in parallel. Step 4 depends on step 3 (dispatch nouns feed the search-term list) and runs after dispatch returns. Step 5 is on-demand.\n\n0. **Preflight / gating**:\n   - `git rev-parse --is-inside-work-tree` to fail fast outside a repo.\n   - `entire version` to verify the CLI exists.\n   - Treat both `entire dispatch` and `entire search` as auth-gated operations. Local verification in this repo shows `entire dispatch --since 1d --voice neutral` fails with `dispatch requires login — run \\`entire login\\`` and `entire search \"\" --json --limit 1 --date month` fails with `not authenticated. Run 'entire login' to authenticate`.\n   - On either auth error, stop before printing the `Entire Project Overview:` header …4797 chars truncated…plugins/marketplace.json` and `.opencode/plugins/entire.js` do not need changes because they do not carry per-release versioned skill metadata.\n- Bump every versioned manifest that ships this repo from `0.3.0` → `0.4.0`: `package.json`, `gemini-extension.json`, `.claude-plugin/plugin.json`, `.codex-plugin/plugin.json`, `.cursor-plugin/plugin.json`, and `.claude-plugin/marketplace.json`.\n- Add a section to `README.md` under \"Skills\" describing `project-overview` (one entry consistent with the existing four).\n\n### Delivery\n\nSingle PR. The change is one new skill file, one README section, and a coordinated metadata/version update across the existing plugin manifests — still well under the threshold that would justify phasing.\n\n### Implementation checklist\n\n1. Create `skills/project-overview/SKILL.md` with:\n   - frontmatter (`name`, `description`)\n   - `Entire Project Overview:` first-response header contract\n   - preflight/auth/error rules\n   - the single-flow command sequence above\n   - drill-down follow-up behavior using `entire explain --checkpoint`\n2. Update `README.md`:\n   - add `project-overview` to the Skills catalog with a concise behavior summary\n   - add 2-3 natural-language examples to Quick Start (for example: \"give me a repo overview\", \"onboard me to this codebase\")\n3. Bump all versioned release manifests from `0.3.0` to `0.4.0`:\n   - `package.json`\n   - `gemini-extension.json`\n   - `.claude-plugin/plugin.json`\n   - `.codex-plugin/plugin.json`\n   - `.cursor-plugin/plugin.json`\n   - `.claude-plugin/marketplace.json`\n4. Manually validate in an Entire-enabled repo:\n   - authenticated run: invoke the skill and confirm all four sections appear, with checkpoint-based drill-down suggestions\n   - unauthenticated run: confirm the response suppresses the header and instructs `entire login`\n   - low-activity repo: confirm the skill keeps the header, emits architecture/contributor sections, and explicitly says the narrative/hot-file section is thin or empty\n   - packaging metadata: confirm each plugin/extension manifest still points at `./skills/` and advertises version `0.4.0`\n\n## Alternatives Considered\n\n- **Generate a persistent `ONBOARDING.md`.** Rejected: drifts immediately, becomes a maintenance liability, and the user can always pipe the skill output to a file themselves.\n- **Split into two skills (`repo-overview` + `onboard-me`).** Rejected: same data, same commands, same output — splitting creates two trigger surfaces for one capability and forces the user to know which to invoke.\n- **Have the skill discover `entire` subcommands dynamically via `entire --help`.** Rejected: fragile, slower, and unnecessary — the three canonical commands cover the use case and existing skills hardcode them.\n- **Use `entire activity` instead of `entire dispatch`.** Rejected: `entire activity` is user-scoped (per-user activity overview), not repo-scoped narrative. `entire dispatch` is the one designed to summarize recent agent work over a window.\n- **Use `entire rewind --list` for the checkpoint list.** Rejected: that's the rewind surface and is not a stable contract for \"list checkpoints\"; `entire dispatch` already digests the list with summary intent.\n- **Use `entire search \"\"` to fetch a generic recent checkpoint set.** Rejected: empty-query semantics are undocumented, and local verification was blocked behind authentication anyway. Focused searches derived from repo/domain terms are more explicit and easier to reason about.\n\n## Risks & Open Questions\n\n- **`entire dispatch` latency.** The default 7d dispatch can take several seconds and 30d may be slower. Mitigation: run dispatch in parallel with the architecture/git steps so the user sees a progress beat. **Resolved:** do not add a timeout fallback in v1. Dispatch is the spine of the recent-activity section; falling back to git-only narrative on a slow run would silently degrade the headline output. If real-world usage shows dispatch consistently exceeding ~30s, revisit then with concrete numbers rather than speculation.\n- **Repo without recent agent activity.** A brand-new or low-activity repo will produce a thin narrative section. The plan handles this explicitly, but we should verify the tone reads helpful rather than broken.\n- **Focused search-term quality.** Seeding `entire search` from repo name, top-level directories, and dispatch nouns is more robust than an empty query, but weak term selection